<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr> And then sat there for the next hour buffing and waiting on your MA.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
Actually I didn't even pick a MA until time to keel Rage, because we had a few 60 warriors there.  Yes, we were buffing (one chanter...40ish peeps...trying to lead and buff heh), but we were also waiting on people who wanted to be there for Lash's final epic battle, and trying to get all the info we could on the &quot;new&quot; Rage.  I had no idea how difficult he would be, seeing as that was my first time going against him.  He wasn't nearly as difficult as I expected, and we hardly had any deaths.<br>
<br>
If we had had to, we could've gotten minimal buffs and keeled him with the groups we had there within 15 minutes, although I would've been very nervous doing that against a dragon I had never fought before.  My &quot;record&quot; (old Rage) for hearing Rage was up, gathering a force, getting peeps ported to LS, getting to Naggy's lair, grouping, buffing, spawning and slaughtering rage is under 30 minutes for all if it for Mindaru's epic.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr> but for many instances/people, that's NOT the case, they really spend 1-2-3-4 hours getting people there, buffing them...oops wrong buffs. rebuff. oh 9 people LD. etc etc.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
Yes, there are not many peeps out there who are stellar at organizing and leading raids, and there are always noobs who have never been on such a raid and don't know that to do.  Should they be punished for that?  I see it as a skill you do or don't have -- some peeps are natural organizers/leaders and can perfect that skill, some are just not.  I don't feel like anyone has the right to run someone over simply because they are not good at it.  Now if they literally cannot get people there and keel rage, that's different, but if they are capable of it given a reasonable amount of time and effort, I do think it's very wrong to run them over.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr> But at what point does that become ludicrious? 1 hour? 2? 6?<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
For a brand new spawn that hardly anyone knows anything about, I'd say an hour or an hour and a half is fair.  Now that I know what I'm up against, I doubt I'd ever take longer than 30-45 minutes to assemble and keel Rage.  But again, I don't feel it's fair to punish those who work just as hard but just aren't quite as good at organizing.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr> while they pretend like they've never been on a vox raid and learned how to buff.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
That's something else -- I don't know where some of those peeps came from the other day, friends of Brizzo's or Lash's or just decided to join us, but man there were some who had no clue how to buff for a dispelling dragon! :P<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr> I have an issue with the mentality behind the roll and the people that want a list for Rage, and what I think it teaches people.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
Ok let me explain it to you again.  There was NO LIST involved here.  Both clerics camped rage and saw him up at about the same time.  They didn't put their names on a list or a calendar and wait for &quot;their turn.&quot;  They had no reservation and nothing handed to them.  They simply got there at the same time and had to find a way to resolve it.  Your method of resolving it would've (apparently) been to try to run the TRK forces over.  Brizzo's and Lashanna's was to roll.<br>
<br>
What on earth does that have to do with a list?<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr> Why does this offend so many people, that I can be so anti such a concept, and *still* do the right thing<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
